Subject: Re: Extrusion problem
Date:    Tuesday, 27 June 1995 04:03:50 
From:    SGiff68285@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

In a message dated 95-06-26 14:03:18 EDT, bmolsen@bvu-lads.loral.com (Brad
Molsen) writes:

>       Hello all, What I hope I get in response to this inquiry is some
>simple explaination of something I have overlooked or some setting I
>neglected to set. You see the following has taken well over an hour of my
>time on a project I'm working on, far tooo long for what should be a slam
>dunk to accomplish, something I've even done before numerous times but, I
>CAN'T GET IT TO WORK THIS TIME AND IT'S DRIVING ME NUTS!!!!

Brad,  You probably will have figured it out by the time you recieve this,
but here goes.  When extruding an edge from within a 3d object you must have
the objects local axis pointing in the right direction.  In other words your
Y axis must be pointing in the direction of the extrusion.  You also have to
have the path axis pointed in the same direction.  Hope this works.

Stephen G.


                       @{"           Thread          367" link IML-367}
                       @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode


@node IML-478 " MSG-478  Subject: Re: Extrusion problem
@toc contents

Subject: Re: Extrusion problem
Date:    Tuesday, 27 June 1995 05:48:35 
From:    Valleyview@aol.com


  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------  

I'm no expert at this, but see if this makes sense.
As I see it the extrusion will only follow the path in one direction, the
original "y" direction.  Rotating the path's axis will not change the
direction of travel.  As I figure you must have your path backwards and must
rotate your path 180 degrees.  It's probably best to not rotate your path's
axis, that way you know it will always follow in the "y" direction.
I've tried changing the object's axis and the path's axis and they have no
effect on the extrusion at all.  The only thing that affects the extrusion is
the direction of the path itself, not its axis.

Rick

